	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Subsidised vessel transfers to tsunami-hit countries: a precedent for the ACP?</h1>

			
			<h4>
												31 March 2005
										</h4>

					</header>


				<div class="intro">

						<p> The EU Fisheries Council adopted an EC proposal to subsidise the transfer of decommissioned fishing vessels to tsunami-hit countries on March 14th 2005.</p>

		</div>
		
		
					<p> Until June 30th 2006, vessels between 5 and 20 years old, not using towed gear, may be eligible for permanent transfer to a third country hit by the Indian Ocean tsunami of December 2004, provided that the following criteria are met: </p>
<ol>

<li> the vessel has an overall length of less than 12 metres and is not more than 20 years old; </li>

<li> the member state which authorises the transfer ensures that the vessel is fully seaworthy and suitable for fishing activity, that it is transferred to a region affected by the tsunami for the benefit of the fishing communities, and that adverse effects on the fisheries resources and the local economy are avoided; </li>

<li> the transfer meets the needs identified by the assessment of the FAO and is in accordance with the third country's requests.</li>

</ol>
<p>
 The FAO issued a press release in late February, entitled 'Why not just any fishing boat will do', warning that a harmful build-up of excess fishing capacity must be avoided in the countries hit by the tsunami. It added that 'inappropriate boat and gear types could harm the environment, doing further damage to the underwater habitat', while also cautioning that new boats and equipment must match local customs, conditions, and fishery productive capacities. If they do not, fishermen's operating costs could end up being more than their incomes, effectively putting them out of business. <br /> </p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
<a href="http://europa.eu.int/eur-lex/lex/LexUriServ/site/en/com/2005/com2005_0036en01.pdf" target="_self">Proposal for a Council Regulation amending Regulation (EC) No 2792/1999...</a> </p><p>

<a href="http://www.fao.org/newsroom/en/news/2005/89901/article_89917en.html" target="_self">FAO press release 'Why not just any fishing boat will do', February 21st...</a> <br /> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> Because of the impact that vessel transfers could have by causing over-fishing and by creating direct and unfair competition with local fleets, EU funding for the transfer of fishing vessels to third countries was stopped at the end of 2004.</p><p> The reintroduction of these subsidised transfers is now being reconsidered under two schemes:</p>
<ul>

<li> the decision to transfer vessels to tsunami-hit countries; </li>

<li> the fisheries partnership agreements to be signed between the EU and ACP countries.</li>

</ul>
<p> Given that similar social and ecosystems conditions prevail in both ACP coastal states and tsunami-hit countries, it would be important for ACP countries to review the conditions established for the subsidised transfer of EU vessels to tsunami-hit countries in the context of the EU's proposal for EU-ACP FPAs. Criteria such as the age of the vessel (between 5 and 20 years old), the exclusion of vessels designed for using towed gears (such as trawling), the responsibility to ensure that vessels are fully seaworthy, that the transfer will be for the benefit of the fishing communities, and that adverse effects on the fisheries resources and the local economy are avoided are particularly pertinent.</p><p> In theory, the reference to the FAO for needs-assessment prior to transfer is also of interest. But in practice, the EU has simply ignored the FAO's advice and sent boats without checking with the FAO.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
